/*!

\page mod_dcmseg dcmseg: a library for working with segmentation objects

This module contains classes to deal with DICOM Segmentation objects. It can
handle shared and fractional segmentations and is able to create, load, modify
and save them. Several checks (as possible) make sure that only valid
Segmentations objects can be written. This module makes heavy use of the
\ref mod_dcmiod "dcmiod" module for managing common IOD attribute as well as
the \ref mod_dcmfg "dcmfg" module to manage the functional groups required for
Segmentation objects.

The main class of this module is:
\li \b DcmSegmentation

\section dcmseg_Labelmap_background Label Map Background / Pixel Padding Value

For Label Map Segmentations every pixel value occurring in the Pixel Data must be
described by an Item of the Segment Sequence. A single value (typically 0) may be
designated as \e background by means of Pixel Padding Value (0028,0120) in the
General Equipment Module, in which case the corresponding Segment carries the
Segmented Property Type Code (DCM,125040,"Background"). Pixel Padding Range Limit
(0028,0121) is never used for segmentations.

How DcmSegmentation handles this depends on whether the object is created from
scratch or read from an existing file.

\par Creating a segmentation from scratch
Call \c setBackgroundPixelValue() (default value 0) to designate the background.
It immediately inserts a Background segment at that value, using Segmented Property
Category Code (SCT,309825002,"Spatial and Relational Concept") and Type Code
(DCM,125040,"Background"), with Segment Algorithm Type MANUAL, by default; the codes
can be overridden (overload), and all other attributes (label, Recommended Display
CIELab Value, algorithm, ...) adjusted afterwards via \c getSegment(). Re-designating
the same value with different codes refreshes the existing Background segment's codes
in place (other customizations are preserved). Only a single Background segment is
kept: changing the background value removes the previously created Background segment
and inserts a new one at the new value (the Pixel Data is not modified). Only an
actual Background segment is ever removed this way; designating a value already
occupied by a \e non-Background segment is rejected (that segment is never clobbered).
Alternatively, you may leave the background value unassigned: the
default handling mode for objects created from scratch is DcmSegTypes::BGH_AddSegment,
which inserts a Background segment automatically on writing \e only for the single
background value (0 by default), and only if that value occurs in the Pixel Data
without a Segment. Any \e other pixel value left without a Segment makes writing
fail in this mode (it must be described explicitly, or a more lenient mode chosen).

\par Reading an existing file
On reading (including \c loadConcatenation()), Pixel Padding Value is interpreted
to designate the background, and a warning is emitted for any pixel value not
described by a Segment, for a Pixel Padding Value that references no Segment, and
for one that references a Segment not typed as Background (DCM,125040). A Pixel
Padding Value encoded as SS (signed) is non-conformant for a Labelmap (whose Pixel
Representation is always unsigned); it is normalized with a warning i.e. a
non-negative value is converted to US and used, a negative value is removed. The
default handling mode for loaded objects is DcmSegTypes::BGH_Warn, so a "foreign"
object is never modified automatically when it is re-written: its Pixel Padding
Value is preserved (never dropped) and only a warning is issued for a missing
Background segment. Select DcmSegTypes::BGH_AddSegment to let DcmSegmentation
insert the missing segment or DcmSegTypes::BGH_Error to make the write fail
when a Background segment is missing.

\par The background is the single source of truth
A Labelmap's background is held internally as a single designated pixel value
(the "lead"). It is set by \c setBackgroundPixelValue(), interpreted from Pixel
Padding Value when reading, or established automatically under \c BGH_AddSegment.
Both Pixel Padding Value (0028,0120) and the Background segment are \e derived
from this lead when writing, so they can never disagree or go stale. A Pixel
Padding Value that is present but for which no background has been designated yet
(e.g.\ set directly via \c getEquipment(), or read from a file) is adopted as the
designated background; once designated, the value leads and a previously written
(possibly stale) element can never override it.

| Situation (Labelmap) | Pixel Padding Value written | Background segment |
| --- | --- | --- |
| background designated, Segment exists at its value | yes (the designated value) | kept |
| background designated, no Segment at its value | yes | added if mode is \c BGH_AddSegment; \c BGH_Warn / \c BGH_Ignore warn only; \c BGH_Error fails |
| no background designated | no | (none) |
| non-Labelmap | no (never written) | (n/a) |

\par Handling modes
DcmSegTypes::E_BackgroundHandling (set via \c setBackgroundHandlingMode()) controls
how pixel values not covered by a Segment are treated on writing:

| Mode | Behavior when a pixel value is not described by a Segment | Default for |
| --- | --- | --- |
| \c BGH_AddSegment | Adds a Background segment for the background value; any \e other uncovered value fails the write | objects created from scratch |
| \c BGH_Error | Writing fails if any pixel value is uncovered | (none) |
| \c BGH_Warn | Tolerates a single uncovered value with a warning; two or more fail the write | objects read from a file or dataset |
| \c BGH_Ignore | Writes regardless, with a warning per uncovered value | (none) |

So the default is \c BGH_AddSegment when creating a segmentation from scratch and
\c BGH_Warn when reading an existing file or dataset; \c BGH_Error and \c BGH_Ignore
are never defaults and must be selected explicitly via \c setBackgroundHandlingMode().

*/
